<div class="hero"><div class="container">
<h1>Can I Buy a Car While in Chapter 13 in Tennessee?</h1>
<p class="subtitle">Yes - but you need court permission first. Buying a car during <a href="https://chapter7vs13.org/" title="Chapter 13">Chapter 13</a> requires filing a motion, getting trustee approval, and showing the purchase fits your budget.</p>
</div></div>
<div class="container">
<div class="quick-answer"><strong>Quick answer:</strong> You can buy a car during <a href="https://chapter7vs13.org/" title="Chapter 13">Chapter 13</a> in Tennessee, but you must file a Motion to Incur New Debt and get court/trustee approval before signing anything. The court will evaluate whether the purchase is necessary and affordable within your plan.</div>
</div>
<section><div class="container">
<h2>The Process: Step by Step</h2>
<div class="step-grid">
<div class="step-card"><div class="step-num">1</div><h3>Get Pre-Approved</h3><p>Find a lender willing to work with Chapter 13 debtors. Get the terms in writing - vehicle, price, interest rate, monthly payment.</p></div>
<div class="step-card"><div class="step-num">2</div><h3>File the Motion</h3><p>File a Motion to Incur New Debt with the Eastern, Middle, and Western Districts of Tennessee bankruptcy court. Include all purchase details and an updated budget.</p></div>
<div class="step-card"><div class="step-num">3</div><h3>Court Approval</h3><p>The trustee reviews and may object. If no objection, the court typically grants the motion within 2-3 weeks. Do not sign anything until approved.</p></div>
</div>
</div></section>
<section><div class="container">
<h2>What the Court Wants to See</h2>
<div class="card">
<ul>
<li><strong>Necessity:</strong> Is the vehicle necessary for work, medical appointments, or family needs? Luxury vehicles are almost always denied.</li>
<li><strong>Affordability:</strong> Can you make both the car payment AND your <a href="https://chapter13plan.org/" title="Chapter 13 plan">Chapter 13 plan</a> payment? The court will review your current budget.</li>
<li><strong>Reasonable terms:</strong> Interest rates above 20-25% may be questioned. The court wants to see you are not being exploited.</li>
<li><strong>Vehicle value:</strong> A used car in the $5,000-$15,000 range is typical. Requests for new or expensive vehicles face heavier scrutiny.</li>
<li><strong>Down payment source:</strong> The court may ask where the down payment is coming from. It should not come from plan payments or exempt funds earmarked for creditors.</li>
</ul>
</div>
<div class="alert">Do NOT sign a purchase agreement, make a deposit, or take possession of a vehicle before the court grants your motion. Unauthorized debt during Chapter 13 can result in case <a href="https://dismissedbankruptcy.org/" title="dismissal">dismissal</a>.</div>
</div></section>
<section><div class="container">
<h2>Interest Rates and Lender Options</h2>
<div class="card">
<p>Borrowers in active Chapter 13 cases face limited lender options and higher interest rates. Typical options in Tennessee include:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Credit unions:</strong> Often the best rates for Chapter 13 borrowers. Some Tennessee credit unions specifically work with bankruptcy filers.</li>
<li><strong>Subprime auto lenders:</strong> Companies like Capital One Auto Finance, Westlake Financial, and DriveTime specialize in lending to borrowers in bankruptcy. Rates range from 12-24%.</li>
<li><strong>Buy-here-pay-here dealers:</strong> Available but typically the worst terms. Interest rates can exceed 25%, and vehicle quality is often poor.</li>
<li><strong>Section 506 <a href="https://section1192.org/" title="cramdown">cramdown</a>:</strong> If your current vehicle loan is more than 910 days old, you may be able to reduce the balance to the vehicle's value through your <a href="https://chapter13plan.org/" title="Chapter 13 plan">Chapter 13 plan</a> rather than buying a new car.</li>
</ul>
</div>
</div></section>
<section><div class="container">
<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
<details class="faq-item"><summary>Can I buy a car while in Chapter 13 in Tennessee?</summary><div class="answer"><p>Yes, but you need court approval. You must file a motion with the bankruptcy court requesting permission to incur new debt. The trustee and court will evaluate whether the purchase is necessary, whether you can afford it within your plan, and whether the terms are reasonable.</p></div></details>
<details class="faq-item"><summary>Do I need trustee approval to buy a car in Tennessee Chapter 13?</summary><div class="answer"><p>Yes. In Tennessee, as in all states, you must get trustee approval before taking on new debt during Chapter 13. The trustee will review the purchase price, interest rate, monthly payment, and whether it fits within your budget and plan obligations.</p></div></details>
<details class="faq-item"><summary>What interest rate can I expect when buying a car during Chapter 13?</summary><div class="answer"><p>Interest rates for borrowers in Chapter 13 are typically higher - often 15-25% from subprime lenders. Some credit unions and specialized lenders work with Chapter 13 debtors at better rates. The court may reject a purchase with an unreasonably high interest rate.</p></div></details>
<details class="faq-item"><summary>How do I file a motion to buy a car in Chapter 13?</summary><div class="answer"><p>You or your attorney file a Motion to Incur New Debt with the bankruptcy court. The motion should include the vehicle details, purchase price, interest rate, monthly payment, and an updated budget showing you can afford both the car payment and your plan payment.</p></div></details>
<details class="faq-item"><summary>Can I lease a car during Chapter 13 in Tennessee?</summary><div class="answer"><p>Leasing during Chapter 13 is treated the same as buying - you need court approval. Some courts view leases less favorably because they do not build equity. The total lease cost will be compared against purchasing.</p></div></details>
<details class="faq-item"><summary>What happens if I buy a car without court approval?</summary><div class="answer"><p>Taking on new debt without court approval is a violation of your Chapter 13 plan. The trustee may file a motion to dismiss your case or convert it to <a href="https://whatischapter7.com/" title="Chapter 7">Chapter 7</a>. The unauthorized debt could also be treated as fraudulent.</p></div></details>
</div></section>
